    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-04-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-04-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="340"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d340">
                <head>340. National Security Study Memorandum 123<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d340fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H–Files), Box H–182, National Security
                        Study Memoranda, <gloss target="#t_NSSM_1">NSSM</gloss> 123. Top Secret;
                        Sensitive. A copy was sent to the Chairman, Joint Chiefs of Staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-04-17">April 17, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>US–<gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> Nuclear Relations</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a study be prepared to review current issues of
                    nuclear cooperation with Great Britain.</p>
                <p>In particular, the study should address:</p>
                <p>1. The extent to which we are already committed to assist the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> in improving its strategic nuclear force under
                    existing agreements.</p>
                <p>2. The implications of US assistance to the British in their efforts to improve
                    the capability of their present Polaris systems through the “project definition
                    phase.”</p>
                <p>3. The long run implications for the US of a deeper involvement in the <gloss
                        target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> effort to develop and deploy an improved Polaris
                    system, including an assessment of British strategic objectives and a possible
                    future <gloss target="#t_UK_1">UK</gloss> request for <gloss target="#t_MIRV_1"
                        >MIRV</gloss> technology.</p>
                <p>This study will be prepared by an Ad Hoc Group comprising representatives of the
                    addressees and the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> staff and chaired by the
                    Chairman of the <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Political
                    Military Group. The completed study, which will be considered by the Senior
                    Review Group, should be forwarded to the Assistant to the President for National
                    Security Affairs not later than May 10.<note n="2" xml:id="d340fn2">
                        <ref target="#d344">Document 344</ref>. The <gloss target="#t_SRG_1"
                            >SRG</gloss> did not meet to discuss the completed study.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_KHA_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
